Scientists found a way of detection of related stars
Astrophysicists from the Californian university in Santa Cruz studied turbulent mixing and its influence on chemical homogeneity in star clusters.
It is expected that discovery of experts will allow to look for among stars related, that is arisen from one cluster.
Authors published results of the researches in the Nature magazine, and briefly it is possible to get acquainted with them on the website of university.
The turbulent mixing in gas clouds preceding formation of stars is the reason of an identical chemical composition of blizlezhayshy stars.
Even if the newly formed star leaves then a star cluster, it is possible to determine the place of its birth and the region of formation of stars relatives by its chemical composition.
Earlier scientists had doubts that evolution of a star out of a cluster can lead to emergence of differences in its chemical composition from that at relatives in a cluster.
The results of modeling which are carried out by astrophysicists show that such differences should not appear.
In the research experts by means of a supercomputer simulated two streams of interstellar gas which together created a cloud.
This object during several million years under the influence of own gravitation will be transformed to a cluster in which protostars begin to be formed.
Scientists added indicating dye to initial gas streams and established that thanks to fast turbulent mixing in a cloud high degree of chemical homogeneity is reached.
As astrophysicists consider, their research proves that it is possible to look for stars relatives on a chemical composition, and also to define possible regions of formation of such objects.
