Remembering very American ideal of the fact that labor rights are human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis offered the bill under which the organization of labor unions is protected as civil law.
"Where labor unions, there and jobs of middle class", Ellison, the democrat from Minnesota who is a cochairman of the Congress of Progressive Fraction says.
That is why I am proud to introduce the Employee Empowerment Act together with a symbol of the movement for the civil rights by John Lewis.
This innovative bill will give to workers the same legal opportunities at discrimination of the organization of labor unions, as at other forms of discrimination, stopping strengths of opponents of labor unions
Change of the National Labor Relations Act so that to allow the workers facing discrimination for participation in the organization of labor unions, to look for justice in civil courts - and to receive compensation of damage and penal payments - a reasonable and necessary initiative.
However it, undoubtedly, not a radical initiative - at least, according to the American standards.
Actually, the best way to understand what is offered by Ellison, Lewis and coauthors of the bill, - to remember very American thought.
Despite a battering which labor unions took in recent years - in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states throughout the whole country - Americans once supported the countries of the whole world in accepting, expand and respect labor rights.
There was time which is remembered still by millions of Americans when this country at the same time protected democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of press and the right for the organization.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, the general Douglas McArthur and his assistants helped the country to adopt the constitution made so that to guarantee that the militarized Hideki Todzyo's autocracy was replaced with democracy.
Completely realizing that workers and their labor unions play a role in formation of new Japan, they included the text which directly recognized that "the right of workers for the organization, both for negotiations, and for collective action is guaranteed".
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, the general Dwight David Eisenhower and his assistants helped Germans to write the constitution which guaranteed that Adolf Hitler's fascism was replaced with strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers will need to be organized and be heard in the new state, Germans included article which openly said: "The right to form associations with the purpose to protect and improve labor and economic conditions will be guaranteed to each person and each profession or a field of activity.
Agreements which limit or seek to strike at this right, will not have validity; the measures directed to these purposes will be recognized as illegal.
When the former first lady Eleanor Roosevelt was the chairman of the International Commission on Human Rights which made the Universal Declaration of Human Rights which in 1948 will be adopted by the United Nations as the world agreement, Roosevelt and originators included a guarantee that "everyone has the right to organize and enter labor unions for protection of the interests".
Generations Americans took for granted the basic provision that labor rights are human rights.
When this country advised other countries how to create civil and democratic societies, Americans explained that the right for the organization of labor unions - and on that this labor union participated as the equal partner in collective negotiations with corporations and government agencies - has to be protected.
Now, when these rights take the battering in America, wisely, really, to return to the American ideal of the fact that the working people have to have the right for the organization and for that their voices were heard in free and open society.
As the Reverend Martin Luther King Jr. told fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the trade-union movement did not undermine nation force, but increased them.
Raising a standard of living of millions, labor unions wonderfully created the market for the industry and lifted the whole nation on unimaginable level of production.
Those who attack labor unions, forget this simple truth, but history remembers them.
History remembers, as should we.
Official recognition of labor rights as human rights - and expansion of protection of the civil rights to prevent discrimination against the organization of labor unions - was about to happen long ago.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis revive ideals which historically expanded America and made the promise of democracy reality.
The judge temporarily blocks the law which could close all abortive clinics in Louisiana
In the USA the federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked introduction of the law of Louisiana about which his supporters say that it, most likely, will close all five abortive clinics in the state.
According to this measure which was signed to execution by the governor of Louisiana Bobbie Dzhinadl in June and had to come into force on September 1, doctors who perform abortions would be obliged to have powers of reception of patients in hospital in a radius of 30 miles from their practice.
Nevertheless, the decision of the judge means that currently doctors can continue to perform legal abortions, continuing to look for such powers.
"It will be authorized to claimants to work legally, continuing actions for obtaining powers", the judge John deGravelles wrote in the decision.
Hearing will be appointed within a month on which the judge will pass more constant decision on this law.
Abortion rights activists heartily welcomed this decision, the last in series of decisions against similar measures, saying that it will give to doctors more time for obtaining hospital powers.
"Today's decision guarantees that women of Louisiana will be protected from the artful law which aspires to depriving of them health and the rights", Nancy Northup, the president and the head of the Center for the reproductive rights who submitted a claim for a stop of operation of the law on behalf of three of five clinics of the state told.
Not at once it was obvious whether the decision concerns to doctors from two clinics which did not act as plaintiffs on this case, and also submitted the application for powers of reception.
Louisiana is included into 11 states which adopted similar laws, and courts recognized such measures unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi recently.
Key parts of the Texas law which would close the majority of the remained clinics in this state were blocked by the federal judge on Friday.
Abortion rights campaigners together with the American college of obstetricians and gynecologists and the American medical association say that laws on powers of reception impose on doctors of restriction, not being necessary from the point of view of medicine.
Opponents of abortions object that such measures are directed to protection of women's health though some also noted their positive effect in closing of clinics.
Only one doctor who performs abortions in Louisiana has powers of reception in hospital, reported the Center for the reproductive rights.
If all other doctors in the state are forced to cease to carry out this procedure, this doctor, being afraid for the safety, would cease to carry out this procedure, the group reported.
Criticizing this decision, officials of Louisiana told that they will not punish the doctors performing abortions while their applications for powers of reception wait for the decision.
What will lead introduction of quotas for domestic goods to
Not less than a half of products by each type of goods in assortment of distribution networks have to be the Russian production, the deputy of the State Duma from Just Russia fraction Oleg Nilov considers.
