Deputies suggested to accelerate entry into force of the law on personal data
In case of success of an initiative, data of Russians cannot be stored on servers abroad since January 1, 2015
The bill providing transfer of the date of entry into force of already adopted law on personal data of Russians - since September 1, 2016 for January 1, 2015 is introduced to the State Duma.
The initiative is placed in base of legislative activity of the lower house.
Deputies of the State Duma Vadim Dengin, Yaroslav Nilov (LDPR), Evgeny Fedorov ("United Russia"), Vladimir Parakhin ("Just Russia") and Alexander Yushchenko (CPRF) acted as her authors.
Such change, according to authors of an initiative, will promote more expeditious and effective ensuring the rights of citizens of the Russian Federation for safety of personal data and observance of secret of correspondence in information and telecommunication networks.
The law which entry into force parliamentarians hurry obliges to store the personal data of Russians processed on the Internet in the territory of the Russian Federation.
He also makes obligatory entry, systematization, accumulation, storage, specification and extraction of personal data of citizens of the Russian Federation, in the databases located in the territory of Russia and also the indication of the data on the location of such databases.
Besides, the law gives Roskomnadzor the right on the basis of a judgment to limit access to information processed with violation of the legislation of the Russian Federation in the field of personal data.
The law also offers creation of so-called "black lists" of the websites violators - the automated information system "Register of Violators of the Rights of Subjects of Personal Data".
This law was adopted by the State Duma in the summer.
As authors of the bill Andrey Lugovoi and Vadim Dengin spoke on behalf of LDPR and Alexander Yushchenko from the CPRF.
Dengin and Yushchenko are also one of authors of the present bill of transfer of the date of entry into force of already adopted law.
Those who in the Russian Federation has no data-centers should pay for rent
Commenting on the bill introduced today to the State Duma the first deputy head of State Duma Committee on information policy Leonid Levin declared that he does not see problems for transfer of the date of entry into force of the law on protection of personal data.
According to him, those companies which by January 1, 2015 will not have own storages of personal data of Russians in the territory of the Russian Federation will be able to rent them, for example, "at Rostelecom which repeatedly said that they are ready to provide the servers for rent and already provides the servers, at Mail Group, at the western companies which already provide today the servers".
"Besides there are several independent data-centers ready to cooperate in this area", - he added.
"If the companies make the decision to carry out the law and to continue to work at the territory of the Russian Federation, I do not see problems - they will have technological capabilities for placement", - Levin summed up.
Controversial bill
Right after the publication of the bill the Russian association of electronic communications stated fear that in case of adoption of the bill Russians will not be able to use many global Internet services any more.
In particular, it is about services of online booking of air tickets and hotels.
According to association, "the bill deprives of subjects of personal data - the rights to dispose of own data imperatively defining citizens of the Russian Federation that their record, systematization, etc. have to is provided only in the databases located in the territory of the Russian Federation".
In the statement of RAEC it is emphasized that creation of the mechanism of informing the user about where record, systematization of his personal data is carried out would be more effective measure.
In that case itself will be able to choose in what territory the specified actions will be made.
Adoption of similar bills of "localization" of personal data in other countries led to leaving of global services and to essential economic losses.
