The ICR terminated Tu-204 crash investigation to Vnukovo
The Investigative Committee of Russia (ICR) dismissed criminal case upon accident of the Tu-204 plane of Red Wings airline.
The press service of department reports about it.
The decision was made in connection with death of the commander of the aircraft and the flight engineer.
Judicial examination showed that high-speed approach on the landing, non-performance by crew of standard procedures on landing, and also an inadvertent exit of engines to the raised turns of direct draft became the cause of accident.
The Tu-204 plane of Red Wings airline going flight Prague - Moscow, crashed on December 29, 2012 when landing at the Moscow airport Vnukovo.
The aircraft was rolled out of a runway and lit up.
On the scene the commander of the aircraft, the second pilot and the flight engineer died.
Two stewards were brought to medical institutions where subsequently from traumatized died.
Three more stewards hospitalized with heavy injuries passed long-term treatment.
Besides, heavy injuries were received by the driver of the car moving to the accident moment on Kiyevskoye Highway.
Passengers onboard the aircraft were not.
The transport prosecutor's office after accident carried out an inspection during which numerous violations were revealed in Red Wings.
In February, 2013 the license of airline was suspended.
The company resumed work as summer of 2013.
